17
00:03:22,099 --> 00:03:35,099
And another tip, or another tactic, I guess this is a general pyro strategy, but it's mostly a backburner strategy, and I guess it's a spy strategy too, because we're talking about backburner pyro, but that's stay out of people's FOV.

18
00:03:35,099 --> 00:03:45,099
Stay out of people's field of view. If you can look at your screen, this is a good little tactic and little thing to practice, stay in spawn for a second. Stand in spawn and look straight ahead.

19
00:03:45,099 --> 00:04:00,280
Now try to keep a mental note of how far to the left and how far to the right you can see, because those are your blind spots. Right after that ends on the left, or ends on the right, those are your blind spots and people can just walk right over there and you'll never see them.

20
00:04:00,280 --> 00:04:04,580
So try to keep a mental note of those things and use them to your advantage.

21
00:04:04,580 --> 00:04:16,579
It's actually another good piece of evidence to use a higher FOV rather than the default, or a lower FOV. When you change your field of view, you get to see more of the battlefield and more of your peripheral vision.

22
00:04:16,579 --> 00:04:31,579
So I highly suggest if you don't have it done, throw up a higher FOV somewhere around 90. And it's going to be odd at first, it's going to seem a little awkward at first, like you're looking through a tunnel, but you will get used to it and it'll make your gameplay a lot better in the long run.

23
00:04:31,579 --> 00:04:44,949
Speaking from personal experience, I had my Team Fortress 2 FOV set to the default for about four and a half years, and it was only about a year and a half ago when I finally decided I was going to try it and I will never go back.

24
00:04:44,949 --> 00:04:57,949
Every FPS I ever play, at least on PC, is always going to be at at least 90 FOV. At least 85, 80 to 90, because it is night and day, guys. If you get used to it, you will see a huge freaking difference.

